<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Dryness that results from damage to the skin barrier during winter can lead to:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>flaking</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>rough patches</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>cracks</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>redness, in lighter skin tones</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>itching</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>stinging</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>a raw, sensitive-to-the-touch feeling</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>People may experience several of these symptoms at the same time. The right treatment should reduce their severity.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>Treatment for winter dry skin</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Dry and damaged skin needs moisture replenishment. It is best to keep a skin care regimen as simple as possible when treating dry skin. A simple regimen avoids overloading the skin with unnecessary products, such as toners, serums, and heavy makeup.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Using a moisturizer is the best way to rehydrate the epidermis and prevent water loss from the skin. Thick, greasy moisturizers without perfumes are generally the best option. Thinner gels, lotions, and creams can cause stinging when a person uses them on irritated skin.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Moisturizers containing emollients, which include linoleic, linolenic, and lauric acids,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.health.harvard.edu/womens-health/what-to-do-about-dry-skin-in-winter" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">can help</a>&nbsp;smooth the surface of the skin. They fill the spaces between skin cells where there has been a loss of moisture.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Humectants in moisturizers help attract moisture to the skin. Examples of humectants include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>ceramides</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>hyaluronic acid</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>glycerin</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>sorbitol</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Other ingredients, such as lanolin, silicone, and mineral oil, help seal moisture into the skin. They also form a protective barrier to reduce damage from environmental factors.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>According to the&nbsp;American Academy of Dermatology Association, it is very important to apply moisturizer as soon as possible after patting the skin dry following a shower or bath. This approach will seal in as much moisture as possible.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>Preventing winter dry skin</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>When the seasons start to change, people can avoid getting dry winter skin by taking the following steps:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Adjusting skin care regimens:</strong>&nbsp;Skin requires different treatment during colder weather, including the use of a more protective moisturizer. Cutting back on exfoliating scrubs, face masks, and steam treatments will also reduce damage to the skin barrier.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Staying hydrated:</strong>&nbsp;Drinking plenty of waterTrusted Source&nbsp;boosts skin hydration, which helps it stay smooth. Eating foods or taking supplements that contain&nbsp;omega-3&nbsp;or&nbsp;omega-6&nbsp;fatty acids might also help.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Using a humidifier:</strong>&nbsp;This device can introduce moisture back into the air, helping rehydrate the outer layer of skin. Alternatively, a person can place a bowl of water on top of a radiator so that as the heat rises, it carries water vapor along with it.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Limiting exposure to heat:</strong>&nbsp;People can do this by taking a lukewarm bath or shower rather than a hot one and avoiding sitting in front of a fire or heater. Excessive heat can draw vital moisture away from the skin.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><strong>Protecting the skin with clothing:</strong>&nbsp;Many people experience dry skin on the hands, particularly now that regular hand washing and sanitizing have become more commonplace. Wearing gloves in cold temperatures and when washing dishes will help prevent the skin from drying out.</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>When to contact a doctor</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The use of home remedies can improve most cases of dry skin. If they have no effect, a person can contact a healthcare professional, such as a pharmacist, doctor, or dermatologist. These professionals can prescribe the right products or recommend next steps.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>Treatments</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:image {"linkDestination":"custom"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image"><a href="https://www.pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.medicalnewstoday.com%2Farticles%2F323973&amp;media=https%3A%2F%2Fpost.medicalnewstoday.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2Fsites%2F3%2F2020%2F01%2Fexfoliating-bathing-supplies-including-loofa-and-brush.jpg&amp;description=Dry%20skin%20patches%3A%20Causes%2C%20symptoms%2C%20diagnosis%2C%20and%20treatments" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><img src="https://i0.wp.com/post.medicalnewstoday.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/01/exfoliating-bathing-supplies-including-loofa-and-brush.jpg?w=1155&amp;h=1541" alt="exfoliating bathing supplies"/></a><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Using gentle exfoliators may help treat dry patches of skin.</figcaption></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>There are many ways to treat dry skin. This section will cover home remedies and medications.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Home remedies for dry skin include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>exfoliating with a loofah, pumice stone, or scrub to remove dead skin cells, if a doctor recommends it</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>applying ointment or cream regularly, ideally using products that contain humectants, ceramides, or emollients</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>using a humidifier to add moisture to the air</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>applying a cold compress to the affected area</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>adding baby oil to warm bath water or applying it when the skin is damp after a shower</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>using warm instead of hot water when showering or bathing</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>gently patting the skin dry with a towel</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Prescription medicines for treating severe dry skin include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>topical medications, including creams, that contain alpha hydroxy acids or retinoids</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>steroids, including hydrocortisone</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li><a href="https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/10278.php">antibiotics</a></li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>topical antiseptics</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item -->

<!-- wp:list-item -->
<li>antihistamines</li>
<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
